Stop Letting Your Templates Understand Your Domain

7 min read
Just now

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

ViewModels are not unnecessary mapping layers. In enterprise Angular applications, they protect the UI from domain complexity, simplify templates, create stable presentation contracts, and make features easier to evolve.
Your API Model Is Not Your UI Model
One of the most common patterns in Angular applications looks like this:
this.http.get<Customer>('/api/customers/123');The API returns a Customer.
The component stores the Customer.
The template renders the Customer.
Simple.
Direct.
Efficient.
At least in the beginning.
Then the UI starts asking questions the API model was never designed to answer.
The Template Starts Translating the Domain
Imagine the backend returns this:
interface Customer {
id: string;
firstName: string;
lastName: string;
status: 'ACTIVE' | 'SUSPENDED';
membershipLevel: 'STANDARD' | 'PREMIUM';
outstandingBalance: number;
permissions: string[];
}
